{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17642547","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17642547"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:41:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:41:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17950"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17950","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17950"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.05,0.05,0.86,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10664"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78673"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10664","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10664"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17950"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64016"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7180"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24840"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24842"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78673","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78673"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following major landmarks of the skull is the middle meningeal artery most closely associated with?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bregma","Lambda","Asterion","Pterion","Martinicans"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe middle meningeal artery is most closely associated with the \u003Cstrong\u003Epterion\u003C/strong\u003E, which is a region on the lateral aspect of the skull where the frontal, parietal, temporal, and sphenoid bones meet. This area is known to be a weak point in the skull, and trauma to this region can lead to rupture of the middle meningeal artery, resulting in an epidural hematoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBregma\u003C/strong\u003E is the junction where the coronal and sagittal sutures meet, located on the top of the skull, and is not associated with the middle meningeal artery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELambda\u003C/strong\u003E is the point where the sagittal and lambdoid sutures meet, located at the back of the skull.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAsterion\u003C/strong\u003E is the point where the parietal, occipital, and temporal bones meet, located on the posterior aspect of the skull, and is not associated with the middle meningeal artery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMartinicans\u003C/strong\u003E is not a recognised anatomical landmark of the skull and is not relevant to the middle meningeal artery.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The middle meningeal artery runs beneath the pterion, a weak point on the skull where several bones meet.","Injury to the middle meningeal artery can lead to an epidural hematoma, a potentially life-threatening condition.","Understanding the anatomical landmarks of the skull is crucial for diagnosing and managing head injuries."],"references":["Singh, V. (2023). Textbook of Anatomy-Head, Neck and Brain, Volume III-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Patestas, M. A., \u0026 Gartner, L. P. (2016). A textbook of neuroanatomy. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Patel, C. R., Fernandez-Miranda, J. C., Wang, W. H., \u0026 Wang, E. W. (2016). Skull Base Anatomy. Otolaryngologic clinics of North America, 49(1), 9\u201320. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.otc.2015.09.001","Anderson, B. W., Kortz, M. W., Black, A. C., \u0026 Al Kharazi, K. A. (2023). Anatomy, Head and Neck, Skull. In StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64016"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17950"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64016","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64016"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-12T08:10:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-12T08:10:55+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10664"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78673"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Nervous System","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T10:23:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading":{"data":